76561198141211956,Recommended,239250,32745423,Posted: 24 June,all,orionali,"I'm three years late with this review.Pros:First off, thank God, the sequel's more keyboard-friendly thanLoS1. Remember the forced Stone Idol Titan “twirl-left-stick” QTE in the first game that had dumbfounded pretty much everyone who could not afford a controller? Well, now you can turn that sucker off, granting Gabriel the power to auto-succeed all QTEs at the expense of some experience points.TheLoS1skill page has become a skill tree; it's easier to browse and see what skills lead to which. Still, the game funnily “reimburses” you should you go for a NG+. Mildly annoying, but it does show you just how much experience you've accumulated.The combat flows more freely if compared toLoS1and the Somersault move no longer makes you feel like you've cement blocks around your ankles. (Yes, I like Somersault.) Unlike other games I've played (namely Alice: Madness Returns), you get a clear visual/audio indication that your attack did not hit/did no damage. The new Weapon Mastery system gives you an incentive to vary your combos.The character design, the bosses, the voice acting, and the OST. Holy hell, A+. Play the game just for these.The Toy Maker and Inner Dracula deserve special mention.Unbound camera! Finally some use for your mouse/right stick.The atmosphere is amazing, especially if you stop to sightsee.The story is engrossing, and it ramps up the stakes in the last ten minutes, too.Purely IMO here, but I do think Gabriel's one of the finest examples of good video game writing. His depiction of Dracula is nuanced and endearing. Same goes for Alucard, really.Cons:Forced stealth is meh. It's not that particularly hard, mind; the enemies you're expected to slip past are brain-dead. They don't look up, don't ring the alarm at the sight of bats in a pharmaceutical corporation, and blame mosquitoes when you fling a dagger at them. The only exception to this isAgreus, but his AI is just as exploitable. Psst, ignore the bells, wait till he rushes you and Mist Form away.The Xbox prompts stay even if you do not have a controller plugged in. Again, a mild annoyance that very nearly got me killed when the game had asked me to ""press B"" or ""down on the D-Pad"".The cheap hitscan potshots enemies like to take at you when you're out of range (or just performing an aerial combo for too long). Soldiers chuck daggers, heavies chuck axes, demons spit, vampires, uhhh, scream (?)... you get the picture. It becomes infuriating if you're backtracking for collectibles and do not wish to engage them. Of course, you can reciprocate with a Void Projectile/Bat Swarm and be on your merry way, but still. Typical padding.Ultimately, in spite of its flaws and troubled development, it's a good game and is worthy its purchase price. I've already beaten it twice. Too bad it was unjustly panned by critics at its release."
,Not Recommended,239250,9857648,"Posted: 17 April, 2014",all,Sweetz,"As a huge fan of Lords of Shadow 1, I sadly find myself rather disappointed in the sequel.  It seems like every change they made to the gameplay is for the worse.First let's talk about the much lamented stealth sections.  They truly and unequivocally suck.  They are relatively infrequent and certainly not insurmountable, but they simply are not entertaining, often annoying if not outright frustrating, and aren't even logically consistent with the rest of the game. One moment you're ripping the heart out of a monster the size of a building, the next you're hiding from two grunts with guns. I can not fathom the developer's reasoning behind their inclusion to the game.  Who played Lords of Shadow 1 and thought ""You know what would make this game better? Insta-fail stealth segments!""Then there's the combat.  I found the combat in Lords of Shadow 1 quite satisfying even it could be simple at times.  It seems they wanted to up the challenge here, but they did so by making the enemies get staggered less, attack at a much faster rate, and having more attack you simultaneously. The problem with this is not that it makes the game too hard, but you need to guard or dodge so frequently that you rarely have time to execute anything more than the most basic attack combo.  Several of the more powerful attacks have such long windups or leave you open so long that they're nearly useless.  As a result, I'm finding the combat to be less varied and far more tedious than the first game.  Too much time is spent dodging and not rattling off impressive combos.There are also little bits of level design that make me wonder at what point the developers stopped asking whether it was fun in favor of just coming up with tasks for the player to do (much like the stealth sections).  For example there are several timed switches where you'll hit a switch to open a door, and as you get close to the door several enemies will appear.  Spend time fighting the enemies (and likely you'll have to) and you won't make the door in time.  So you walk back to the switch, hit it again and this time you can cross the area unmolested.  It's the most egregious form of repetition to pad playtime and makes no sense in a game that's sufficiently long regardless.  It's the kind of thing that makes you feel like the designer isn't respecting you as a player.If that wasn't enough, even the camera is disappointing.  Some reviewers whined about the fixed cameras of the first game, when the problem was just a few bad angles.  They switched to a controllable behind the back camera here, and while it's perfectly functional, the game has lost the epic vistas and panning shots of the first game that you only get with fixed (or more accurately: not player controlled) camera angles.  As a result, despite environment design that feels roughly on par with LoS1, the game has lost much of the grand feeling of it's predecessor.Now on the plus side, everything that doesn't have to do with the mechanics of the game are at least as good as the original.  The art design and aesthetics are great even if you don't get to appreciate them as much with the narrow camera.  The characters and cinematics are absurd, but in a way that feels fitting and not like it's trying too hard - though it can get close at times.Taken by itself, the game isn't awful, I still found it reasonably entertaining on the whole.  It's just that everything about how it plays feels worse than the original and it's especially disappointing to see so many mistakes made by the developer after the success they had with original."
76561197968514473,Recommended,239250,23533252,"Posted: 13 June, 2016",all,Meat-King©®,"“What is a man, but a miserable pile of secrets.”Castlevania: Lords of Shadow 2 is an action adventure game developed by the company MercurySteam, and the sequel to the 2010 game Castlevania: Lords of Shadow.Atmosphere & presentation:+ Sinister depiction of the game world with dystopian elements.+ Each stage has its own atmosphere and iconic art style of the Castlevania series.+ Obsessive attention to detail regarding level design.+ Extensive concept art section with hundreds of pictures and sketches.o Solid sound effects.o Due to the console based origin a gamepad is recommended, in order to play the game.Combat & gameplay:+ Combat system is solid and reliable.+ Good camera handling in combat and exploration sections.+ Exploration of the surroundings is rewarded with bonus powers and useful trinkets.o Variety of enemies is rather small and champions are too weak.- The stealth sections are an atrocity. An insult to the legendary abilities of the Lord of Shadows.Characters & story:+ Certain characters and story elements from Lords of Shadow and Lords of Shadow – Mirror of Fate are reintroduced and further developed.+ The downloadable content “Revelations” introduces Alucard as a playable character and provides some surprising background information.o Compelling storytelling in the beginning, but it loses momentum towards the end.- Inconsistent character development of Dracula.- The final boss is a cliché.Summary:The second instalment of the Lords of Shadow series offers beautiful visuals and a solid combat system. However, the rest of the game does not reach the level of quality of its predecessor. Despite the strong start it loses its momentum in the middle of the game, and the solution of the conflict between Dracula and his antagonist can be considered a cliché. To add insult to injury, the forced stealth sections are an unnecessary and partially frustrating element.Achievements:Estimated time for 100 % completion: +40 hoursSingleplayer achievements: 56Multiplayer achievements: none"
76561197996223286,Recommended,239250,31045572,Posted: 9 April,all,NeOzguR,"One of the Most Underrated Game EverIf you look at the metacritic score you would think ""This game is not good"" yes? But it is sooooooooo far from the truth. This is a one helluva solid game. Believe me when I'm saying that I enjoyed it's every second. Musics, graphics, voice actings, drama, face emotion, level designs. All of 'em. Just brilliant.If you like the first game you will definitely like this game because they give camera control, fluid control over Dracul and his endless combo. I didn't like these things at the first game because they were so dull. But here... Man it's one the best game since GoW.By the way people hate this game because ""it's not Castlevania"". I don't know about that because i didn't play the old games. Bu this game gives you the control of Dracul and his smooth powers and let me tell you I was thrilled. Especially after the first LoS game.Please do not mind the sh.ty metarcritic notes. This game is solid and SOLID. And that's that.9/10"
76561198004627556,Recommended,239250,12878836,"Posted: 10 November, 2014",all,dante_87,"(DISCLAIMER: Objectively, as a game, Castlevania LoS 2 is a good, overall,  game that has some flaws. However, as a follow up to Castlevania LoS, it is terribly disappointing. My recommendation is based on the game itself, not my disappointment as  a sequel to the original.)Let's start with the GOOD. The combat has been refined in a very nice way and thusly feels a bit more responsive. As in the last game, with the points/experience that you receive from defeating enemies, you can use that to buy additional moves for your weapons, but this time, you have the addition of the chaos claws and void sword AND they have their own moveset on top of the same function as shadow and light magic respectively. Thusly, giving you many combo possibilities. Dodging is smooth, although I would have preferred a roll like the original, or the turning into smoke like Laura in the original game as well. I'm glad for the addition of the free rotating camera that was lacking in the first game.Platforming has also been improved and is much smoother than before.The graphics, very,very nice. However, it seems a bit of a waste since the most of the environments are dank, dark and very similar; unlike the original game where there was a lush forests, autumn ruins, icy castles, dark dungeons, crazy grand canyonesque platforming. Just wasted potential overall, but a great graphics engine nonetheless.Now for the BAD: STEALTH, man oh man, this game never needed stealth to begin with so I don't know why it's even here. Not that I mind stealth, it's just done very, very poorly in this game. The stealth sections were very tedious and boring. It was repetitive and not necessary to the game.Speaking of not necessary, the section where you have to hide from Pan's brother so you don't get one-shotted....ridiculous! You're freaking Dracula, the prince of freaking darkness. Satan is even scared of you in the game, yet, you have to hide from this guy? Again, since this was a stealth portion, it was terrible and necessary.The modern setting, I'll admit that I was excited to check out a modern setting in LoS, but honestly, it felt so out of place, especially the robots and commandos in exo suits. The sections you get to go back to the castle felt much more appropriate and epic.The story, the story this time around, lacked a sense of urgency and purpose. This is probably partly due to that you're now Dracula and you don't care weather thousands of people live or die. I through most of the game, it felt as if I was just trudging along just getting through the game, instead of feeling like I'm making real progress. The story lacked any real revelations, twists or turns, like the original had. It was very one track and lacked anything with real substance. There is no internal struggle like in the first game, any real tragedy with character investment, the story felt like it had a beginning and an end but missing pieces in the middle, not necessarily plot holes, but more so they needed to add elements to make it really interesting.Overall, the game is ok with some flaws. I did have fun with the combat, especially in the intro of the game, but after that, it felt like it was all downhill from there; lack luster story, repetitive environments, terribly implemented stealth. Sadly,  Castlevania LoS 2 just couldn’t meet the standards set by the first. As a huge fan of this series, I'm hugely disappointed. As a gamer, it's a “not bad” game.7/10"
,Recommended,239250,17012922,"Posted: 12 July, 2015",all,Pakkidis,"8.5/10Overview: Third Person Action AdventureThe Good+ The setting is a mixture of a modern city in ruins and Draculas old castle. Both settings provide a nice contrast with each other and are fun to explore+ The first major difference from the original is the ability to control the camera as opposed to having a fixed camera in the first game.+ The second major change is all the levels are interconnected with each other. This provides for a much more immersive and seamless experience with gameplay.+ Combat is more refined than the original and just as fun. You have light magic that does less damage but heals you whenever you damage an enemy and chaos magic that does significantly more damage but is slower and has less range. Effectively dodging and switching between your magic meters is fun and engaging. If you played the first game, the combat should offer little surprise to you. One key difference is by using attacks over and over again you can increase your mastery of a certain weapons making them stronger.+ Boss battles have always been a highlight for this series and this game is no exception. Bosses are unique, well designed and will require you to use all your techniques in battle to defeat them.+ the game has plenty of collectables scattered throughout the world+ The game features 16 optional challenges to further extend your game time. Each challenge has a series of objectives that has to be completed in order to complete the challenge.+ option to disable quicktime eventsThe AverageThe story is not awful but it didn't really do much either. It doesn't help that most of the dialogue spoken by the villains is bad.This game has some REALLY annoying enemies that will test your patienceThe BadFor some odd reason the developers decided to include stealth sections in the game. I like stealth games and I like it when developers try to mix up the gameplay but this was just a bad effort. The stealth sections feel very out of place and are not always clear in what you have to do making for some really frustrating trial and error. It also feels very odd that you play a badass destroying most enemies in your path only to reach a section in the level where you have to avoid enemies.ConclusionThis game fixed two of my biggest gripes from the first game. The fact that the levels are interconnected and the ability to actually control the camera make for a much better gameplay experience despite the awful stealth sections. I was a bit baffled that reviewers panned this game pretty badly as I think this game improves the first game in many ways. If you enjoyed the first game then there is no reason why you shouldn't love this game as well, unless of course the modern day setting doesn't appeal to you."
