76561198099260485,Recommended,239250,22506352,"Posted: 18 April, 2016",all,bwDraco,"I'm going to start by saying that my overall experience with this game is more positive than negative. While there are a few issues that detract from the overall experience, they are not serious enough for me to not recommend the game. Some key points follow.The combat system is an evolution of the one in the first game, with significant refinements that make for a very smooth experience. For example, you can dodge and parry attacks even in the air. While the skill trees for each of the weapons may seem labyrinthine at first, if you put some thought into how they're structured and how each of the moves are executed, you'll start to realize how elegantly designed Dracula's moveset is. Gone are the difficult-to-execute combos in the firstLords of Shadow; you now have a broad range of attacks that are easily performed with plenty of versatility for nearly any combat situation.Setting and environmental design is generally excellent. Both in the castle and in the city, there's a great sense of scale, and the level of detail put into the environment is absolutely incredible. Overall, it's designed in the open-world ""Metroidvania"" tradition, with plenty of exploration and discovery. Many level design cues have been taken from theAssassin's Creedseries, which isn't a bad thing since I've always liked their level design; likewise, when not in combat, Dracula himself handles a lot like Connor fromAssassin's Creed III. However, it is not completely flawless; ......in particular, some of the stealth sections need improvement. While the ones involving Golgoth Guards aren't exactly bad, Agreus's maze andCarmilla'sblood curse puzzle are questionably designed, leaving the player very little room for error which can lead to frustration.The story is good, but not great. Dracula as a character has some very nice background but scenario design can be a bit better and the ending is a bit too open-ended.Again, neither of the last two points are enough to take away my recommendation. It's sad that these (relatively minor) flaws in an otherwise well-executed game led to such negative critical reception from several expert reviewers. Playing as the Prince of Darkness himself has been an unforgettable experience for me and I ultimately enjoyed the game.Recommended."
76561197970554803,Recommended,239250,20869778,"Posted: 31 January, 2016",all,Squatingtiger,"I don't think I've ever enjoyed destroying gothic furniture for bonus exp so much....But seriouslyCastlevania lords of shadow 2 was very hard for me to break into. I thouroughly enjoyed the first one, so much so that I was looking for the same "" magic "" in this game, the discovery and newness. Unfortunately it wasn't until about 3-4 hours in I started enjoying it. Perhaps I was trying too much to relive the the wide eyed amazement of the first game. Oh for sure, it's Castlevania, don't get me wrong, the story carries on extremely well from Lords of shadow 1 and mirror of fate and ties the 3 games together but I just didn't "" get it "" until that 3-4 hour mark.Graphically...supurb! I'm really amazed that this game engine looks so good and yet getting a decent framerate of 40-60 fps on full settings.Gameplay is alright, the combat can be monotonous.I enjoyed the story as it carries over from the previous two games.All in all a great game."
,Recommended,239250,30063319,Posted: 20 February,all,MuffinMan,"Mercury steam sequel of their reboot of the Castlevania series takes the ip back to its root of exploring an entire whole castle, where different sections have unique style, mechanics and monsters. It is probably the closest someone got to make a full 3D experience of Castlevania Symphony of the night. As for the first reboot the game is also at its core a spectacle fighting game.The story of the game is suspended between two moments in time. In the present, your character, Dracula, wakes up after a very…very long sleep and faces a the evil deeds that are being made in what remains of his castle, now part of a whole city with a high tech facility rule by evil itself. Dracula also has to gain back his lost powers and it will do so traveling back in time to his old castle. Unlocking new areas and abilities will allow Dracula to travel more and more freely to every part of the levels in the typical Metroidvania style. Enemies will respawn every time in the same place giving you always some challenge. It may though get to become repetitive (a common problem with backtracking in this type of game design). What will not become tiresome is how beautiful the environments are! Especially the old castle, simply stunning. The same effort was not exactly put into enemy design, which are a bit more repetitive than in the prequel (no more mounting on orcs or giant spiders!)The combat system is solid, strikes have impact force despite being almost all whip based and allow for a decent amount of combination, crowd control and power strikes, but not as much as tytles like Devil May Cry or Bayonetta. Mobility during combat is now much improved compared to the prequel, you can dash as much as you want in any direction, which really gives you the sensation of being a superpowered mischevious vampire that moves swiftly and strikes hard! The combat itself did not changed much from the first game. Magic attacks now use a sword and gauntlets instead of different colors of the whip attack, changing a lot the range of actions, but the combo scheme is copied into every weapon set (whip, sword and gauntlet alike).The interesting combat mechanic of the series, the focus mechanic, comes back. This mechanic builds up a meter for chaining combos and variation of techniques used (as the meter of score for Devil May Cry) and is set back to zero if you are hit. Instead of just being linked to a score rating this focus meter is directly linked to the combat. Once it is filled enemies start giving magic refill, which you can absorb to fill up one of your two magic style (healing/defense style with the sword or heavy attack style with the gauntlet).Timing your block properly is probably the most efficient way to build up focus meter and create opening to attack even stronger enemies. The sync block mechanic (such is the name of this timing block thing) will create a sort of light explosion which will stagger enemies and slow time for a bit, great visual effect and good for planning your reposte.I had the impressions that enemies and boss design had a step back compared to the prequel, but it may be due to the amount of time you will have to backtrack (especially for completionists).In conclusion, I liked playing this title as much as the prequel, it is probably a more direct 3D successor to Castlevania than the first Lords of Shadows. It has some flaws for sure, but it a solid title if you wish for a good spectacle fighter with a Castlevania flavor.  I really hope a third title comes out taking the good of Lords of Shadows 1 and 2, combining them and smoothing the mistakes. That would really be a great game…but unfortunately it is Konami we are talking about…so don’t hold your breath."
