,Recommended,239250,9319389,"Posted: 2 March, 2014",all,felek121,Could be better
,Recommended,239250,9278970,"Posted: 27 February, 2014",all,BakedCookie,"First thing's first- many mainstream reviewers heavily underrated this game, sometimes to the point where I wonder if they played a different game. It baffles me even more when they say things along the lines of ""I loved the first game but this doesn't even come close"". That my friends is a lie, it is a lie because Lords of Shadow 2 improves in many areas of the first game and it amounts to it being an overall better game. I'd also like to add that this game performs better on PC than the first one. Let that sink in- this game with a free camera and an hd texture pack performs better than it's fixed point camera, straight up console port predecessor. I'm not entirely sure who was responsible for the port, but whoever it was the port is done well, with all the main options present as well as some gameplay customization thrown in for good measure.THE BADLet's kick it off with the things LoS2 does not do well, because trust me- while it is a great game it is not devoid of flaws and when they pop up, they show. I think we can universally agree that the stealth sections are a pain the the♥♥♥♥♥♥ it's not even that they are boring to some (I personally enjoyed the first two hours of the game where the majority of stealth happens) but that they lack the fidelity to make them truly enjoyable and sometimes that they are kinda going against common sense. The latter comes into play most prominently in one boss pre-fight and one later city stage. Those were the only two places in the game that I was stuck for 15min straight just going ""why game, why would you make me do this"". Aside from the sections where you are stripped of your powers and must rely on stealth (that being the beginning, around 0.5 to 1.5h into the game) the stealth amounts of about 30 minutes of the entire game at maximum. So while it has some clear issues it's not something you'll be doing a whole lot.Another negative point I would nitpick is the level layout design (not the design itself), in that this being an open world game it should be easy to navigate it, however I find myself wondering how to get to that one place I've been to previously and my best bet is to just wonder around until I find it. Now let me be clear- this is not a problem when it comes to the main storyline because for that purpose the game gives you a minimap with a quest marker (and it works very well as a matter of fact) it only becomes a problem when you unlock new powers and want to revisit older areas to collect the things that were previously out of reach. This problem I feel is a direct result of the game being as grand as it is- the sheer amount of vistas, sceneries, ruins and wrecked architecture left little in the way of a 100% clear and intuitive way to traverse it. And in contrast to the stealth sections I feel it would be hard if not impossible to make the world easily accessible without sacrificing some of the great art direction and good design choices. That said the quick travel system that you unlock sometime into the game could offer more places to warp to and not just a few general districts.From a technical aspect the environments, especially in the city sections, could use some higher resolution textures and maybe a bit more detail to boot. Especially on the cars.THE GOODThankfully the game has more than enough to counterbalance it's faults and come on top. Let's start with the combat system because it is pure bliss here. In the first game, while I enjoyed the combat I always felt that launching enemies into the air is completely unviable and that the dodge move was kinda sluggish. That has thankfully been revised in LoS2 and the combat is smooth, fast and very responsive. The dodge is now a dash that can be chained together to either cover distance (combine with sprinting for best results) or quickly angle around an enemy. It is very responsive and can be triggered from both the ground and air, meaning you no longer have to be afraid of going airborne as you can always dodge out of any enemy attack.   The physics of the world have also been altered slightly so that controlling Dracula feels just right. A change from the original is also the Void/Chaos magic which, when activated replace your default blood whip with either the void sword or the chaos claws. These come with their own abilities and mastery trees. It's a great improvement to the old system where activating either would just apply an effect to your combat cross. Here you actually get a different weapon, with different range and different moves. The Void/Chaos magic extends into subweapons which give you a LOT of variety to your combat style. Overall the combat just feels great and rewarding, rarely (if ever) did I feel like it was the games fault when I died, as there is always a technique or an approach that will result in your victory. That said, it is important to learn some enemies patterns as they can sometimes be a pain in the♥♥♥♥♥♥if you forget that said enemy has a certain pattern of unblockable attacks that you must dodge.Onto the visuals then, which I feel are absolutely gorgeous. The animations of every character are great, Dracula himself is very fluid in his movements which is quite critical as you'll be staring at him quite a bit. This shows especially in the platforming bits where Drac jumps from ledge to ledge in quite the Spiderman fashion. The texturework is stellar on the characters, great in the castle and great/good in the city. I wish it was more consistent but for what it, it passes in every respect with just a slap on the wrist for the odd texture in the city. Overall I'd say the game screams high fidelity (and don't even get me started on the facial animations/textures, they are finger-licking good). But what are good graphics without good environments to put the into? Thankfully I feel the game delivers that too. The castle has locations that made me just stop for a few seconds (or was it minutes?) to just take in the surroundings, their creative value being just that high. The city, surprisingly, did too. Granted it has some bland locations when compared to the castle, but it also has some stellar gothic architecture melded with a cityscape with some impressive statues to boot. I feel like the first parts of the city that the player sees really do it injustice at it is mostly based around cubes and blocks (sciences district, I'm looking at you). The other districts offer more variety, and in general I really liked going to the city. It also helps that the enemy design in the city is some of the best I could imagine for this game. I half expected to get some generic futuristic solder or something but instead I got Castlevania's version of the Combine from Half-Life. I think it goes without saying I was most impressed with how they handled it. Enemy design in the castle is equally creative, however I'm going to cop out here and say that the castle is the most memorable enemy. I'm not going to spoil anything here, but let's just say if MercurySteam ever got their hands on the Silent Hill franchise, I would actually anticipate the next installment. To wrap this part up, the art assets, the direction and execution are almost stellar in this game. What keeps is from being truly great are the few bland environments in the city, and some environmental texturework that is not up to snuff at times.CONCLUSIONI'd love to write more but I'm getting close to my word limit, my summary would be that when the end credits rolled I felt like I played a great game and a great final installment to the Castlevania trilogy. It didn't end in a cliffhanger, but it didn't answer everything either (in a subtle manner). If I had to rate the game I'd give it an 8.5/10, the extra 0.5 is for the replay value- after completing the game I only uncovered 30% of secrets and still have challenges to complete. And I can't wait to get back into the fray, completionist style (and trust me, few games do that to me)."
76561198035816354,Recommended,239250,9295728,"Posted: 28 February, 2014",all,EsauD1,"This is a great game, that for some reason got trashed by a lot of gaming sites, for the worst reasons, most of them reviewers sounded like they only played a demo of the game, and went on to make their review. I can easily say this game is phenomenal. Thanks to those guys this might be the last castlevania game like this we  will see in a really long time. One thing that is very  easy to spot is that it does borrow from other titles, but it grabs the great ideas. For instance at one point it reminded me so much of metal gear, and a few minutes later it took me  on an a train ride a la unchardted 2 style both of which were very fun parts of the game. It has very very good looking graphics, an amazing soundtrack, awesome combat system, and a lot of collectibles. The story is pretty cool too I absolutly don't understand again why a lot of the so called professional  critics, scored it so low. I own hundreds of games outside of steam, I know when a game really really sucks to the point of it just being unplayable or not worth my money, but this game is worth every single cent I spent on it. You will really like it if you are into adventure games that make you explore (metroidvania games) or the castlevania series, just take it slowly enjoy the views the atmosphere, learn the combat system, and you will love it."
