76561198072182182,Recommended,239250,12254037,"Posted: 26 September, 2014",all,Zeebrax the Astral Lifejacket,"If you expect this game to be of the same caliber as the sublimeLords of Shadow, prepare for bitterest disappointment.  While the fighting is responsive and the PC optimization is excellent, too much of the game is a mess.The levels, in layout and aesthetic, are by and large atrocious; the magnificent fantasy forests and brooding, vine-choked ruins of the first game have been exchanged for tedious near-future cityscape where 90-degree angles dominate (nice attempt at camouflage with those pretty textures, Mercury Steam, but they can only go so far).   There are a few brief, beautiful segments that take place within Dracula's ""inner castle,"" but these are over too soon and serve to highlight the dull ugliness of the metropolis, which is confusing, repetitive and filled to the boxy margins with generic, endlessly respawning T-Virus monsters.  Yes, you spend most of the game battling urbanites transformed into Biohazard C-stringers by a Satanic biological agent, and they are a dull lot indeed.The worst gameplay sections of all are the stealth bits.  In these, Dracula, who is supposed to be the baddest damn thing in the world, Dracula, who demolishes building-sized gorgons, Dracula, who ultimately succeeds in deep sixingSatan himself, must hide from cyborg guards with plasma rifles who are able to one-shot him on sight!  Aside from making absolutely no sense in terms of the game world, these bitter bits of Metal Gear lite are distinctly unfun.  Hell, you don't even get to kill one of the damn things!  The bad guys should have just sent an army of these cyborg guys after Dracula, thus ensuring the Devil's terrestrial reign forever.The storytelling in Lords of Shadow 2, like everything else in it, seems patchy and incomplete.  In concept, it was a great idea (you'll see this if you stick it through to the end), but the execution is completely slapdash, leaving even some of the most important plot points, particularly the seemingly transdimensional status of Dracula's castle, unexplained.  Most of the time, you'll be unsure ofwhyyou are doing what you are doing.Despite all, I recommend this -- but only for the price of ten or fewer U.S. dollars, and only if the shockingly fun DLC, Revelations, is included.  Surprised?  Well, as I said, the story isn't bad, it's just badly told for the most part; if you are fan of the first Lords of Shadow, you'll want to the experience the unexpectedly cool ending of LOS2.  Also, most of the boss fights are pretty damned great, particularly the epic final battle!Lords of Shadow 2 is a poor Lords of Shadow game and kind of a bad Castlevania game, but it's not really a badgame, just a mediocre one with a few redeeming bright spots.  By all means, give it a whirl when it's on sale."
