,Recommended,239250,9285841,"Posted: 27 February, 2014",all,malt,"I'm not sure I'm playing the same game as review sites are, this is a great game for fans of the first one. There's plenty of opulent set pieces to go with the same emphasis on defensive, carefully paced combat, alongside newly added incentive to try and vary the attacks you use long term to upgrade the power of your weapons. There are a few samey corridor pieces and a few poorly executed ""stealth"" puzzles, but for the most part the game is whips and platforming. If you liked LoS1 and/or Mirror of Fate there are very few reasons you wouldn't like this. Protip: Golgoth guards will spot you when they are standing still, so creep up behind them only when they start moving."
76561198031262604,Recommended,239250,9286855,"Posted: 27 February, 2014",all,The Bored Chairman,"Truly an upgrade to the first game, LoS2 brings a nice change of pace. The gameplay itself is solid, responsive and platforming isn't a chore like it was in the first game (fixed camera and 3D should never mix). The enemies are a nice change of pace, forgoing the traditional fodder spam in previous Castlevania games and the removal of the ""Grab is the only attack that matters"" is nice. Given the track record of 3D Castlevania games, this one is a leap in the right direction. The puzzles are a nice touch, not too difficult and quite creative.That being said, there are parts in the game that will cause you grief. Wandering around the city looking for an objective is tedious and frustrating, especially when the enemies continously respawn. The stealth mechanics are either stupidly easy or very cheap (I have developped a hatred for the fall season). And certain parts of the game will not give you an indication of what is required until you die (and a tip appears on the game over screen).All in all, the game is decent and will cater to fans similar games (God of War, Dante's Inferno, Devil May Cry, Bayonetta) and maybe Castlevania fans (if they are open to the 3D element). Unfortuately, the game's frustrating componants may deter players new to the genre. If the gameplay issues could be adressed, this game could truly be considered the stepping stone for 3D Castlevania games."
