,Recommended,239250,9337290,"Posted: 3 March, 2014",all,TheTerraphobic,"18 hours on record, but it felt like a lot longer and I did barely any of the exploring. Lords of Shadow 2 is a fantastically composed game, with an enjoyable mix of platforming sections and combat, though the balance towards the platforming and forced stealth after the game's introduction is a bit skewed.Combat feels incredibly meaty, and switching weapons mid combat is far more satisfying than the magic system from the previous game, really making combos feel heavy and devastating. Though there is a limited meter for each of the weapons, I found that I barely reached the bottom unless I was obsessing heavily over one. The one complaint is enemies with shields that need to be broken with the chaos claws, and whilst you can backflip over them, the mercenary soldiers seem to be able to rotate instantly, requiring the use of the claws more often than not. There is a plethora of abilities for each weapon, and unless you constantly back and forth between zones grinding enemies for xp, it is highly unlikely you will have unlocked them all by the game's end.Boss battles are big and epic, featuring multiple phases, transitions and enjoyable visuals and backgrounds, the second fight with Volkova being one of the highlights of the game. Lords of Shadow 2 also ignores some of those awkward climbing bosses from the first game, with only a short climbing section featuring in the pentultimate encounter. Whilst it isn't always immediately obvious where to go, swarms of bats linger on ledges Dracula can jump on from the ground, whilst holding a button highlights the path you need to take.The voice acting is superbly well delivered, Patrick Stewart as Zobek owns any scene he's in, and although Gabriel/Dracula's dialogue in the game's introduction is quite hammy, Robert Carlyle really hits his stride as the game's pace picks up, especially in the more emotional engagements with his family.All in all I would recommend Lords of Shadow 2 if you're after a game that's going to last you a good long while, however one thing I would object to is marathoning it as fast as possible (as I did) as you'll find yourself getting burnt out and frustrated quickly."
76561198082834006,Not Recommended,239250,22263727,"Posted: 5 April, 2016",all,Luel,"Castlevania Lords of Shadow 2A wasted opportunityMercury Steam had the chance to close his Castlevania trilogy in a high note, with a golden lock, but instead, all it accomplishes is a terrible failure. I have not reviewed a game in a while but I really need to let out some steam. Lords of Shadow was a great game, a good incarnation of the Castlevania series and the first one to actually manage to pull a good game in 3D. With it's combat mechanics, it's boss fights and a story that I find quite interesting. The first Belmont turns out to be the one transforming into Dracula and the greater evil is Satan. Bravo!Mirror of Fate was a good game, just that. It had a good story, the first time that the Belmont (Vampire Hunters) went on for Dracula's head and how Alucard came to be. Pretty original all around. But it can't compare of course with the first game. And then it came the trilogy closure. Lords of Shadow two. The first game to actually put you in the role of Dracula and in the present. At glance, it's an idea worth exploring, a finale worth telling; to know what happens to Gabriel Belmont now as Dracula and to see if Satan returns. Will Dracula find redemption? At least I know the game won't. The combat mechanics are the same as Lords of Shadow, but now instead of light and shadow magic you have a Void Sword (light) and Chaos Claws (Shadow). Not one change in the mechanics aside from that. If it ain't broke, why fix it?But oh! Mercury Steam tried to step up the game with the world and the map. What a big mistake. The map, instead of being presented as the first game, in which you were advancing from place to place and you could revisit them whenever you wanted and relive the boss fights; now it's just a conglomerate mess. It deviates itself into a sort of open world with a map room every now and then in some locations that help you fast travel from place to place, but it is hard to keep track of where have you been and where you need to go to get all the upgrades. The map is divided in two: the city and the castle. What you may say? We are in the present day right? Yes! We are, but on that later.The city is just dull. All grey, wherever you turn. Generic places, streets, alleys; only for a few landmarks where you fight bosses or big group of enemies. The presentation of the place is lame, it does not encourage the player to explore. The castle has some epic scenarios and places that vary from each other, one time you are on an underground city and another you are exploring a hall; and that's a good thing but unfortunately that is all. The enemies are generic as hell. The demon spawns are so generic and there are so few types of them that you feel like you are battling the same enemies all the game. It is another story for the castle, but nevertheless, there are not so many different types of enemies.And here come the bosses. I don't know where to start. Let's see...There are many bosses on this game and their design is great, but just two of them managed to wake my emotion battling them. The rest of them felt kind of cheap. Also, there aren't any or at least few mechanics whatsoever to kill them. You literally (aside some exceptions) can blast your way through them with brute force. What thing that was a big letdown was the final battle. I was expecting an epic clash and what I received was a boss battle that felt forced and a killing scene that couldn't be more lame, LAME with capital letters, do you hear me mercury steam?Now, onto the point where you are Dracula, the prince of darkness, the dragon, the... Wait... Do I need to hide from this guys because I can't fight them? Do I need to turn myself into rats because of the fear to be killed by them? Am I not the Dragon? A force of darkness to be reckoned with? The one who vanquished Satan?Let that sink in. There are some parts of the game that put you up against some body guards of Satan and you can't fight them, you need to sneak past them transforming into rats or mist; I get it, Dracula can use those skills and I know that he is weakened by his long sleep but there is no part in the game that we face them directly in combat; but oh the final boss? Yeah sure bring it on! I am certain that after that fight, Dracula still needs to sneak from those bodyguards. So in a few words: you never really feel like the dragon.And now, for the final part of this review and my conclusion: the story, if that thing can be called that. The story is just a convoluted mess. Mercury Steam clearly had no idea on how to develop the story and how to end it. The premise is a fantastic one: you are now Dracula and you are about to confront the lord of hell, Satan himself with acolytes around the city paving his way; also, there is something within his mind, dreams (I really don't know what was it) that draws you back to the castle, and when you are there you discover that a corrupted blood, a dark entity is trying to keep Dracula there for all eternity. The story, as I said before, is developed in the present day at Castlevania City and in the Castle. You travel from one another by portals around the world or when a vision comes to play or Trevor appears and guides you to the castle.So this was the ending of the trilogy, of Mercury Steam take on the franchise and what did they do with it? They blow it off. The story is weak, doesn't give a closure and nothing great happens. Dracula sets to stop Satan but ends in a very weak tone for this part and it is never explained why there was dark blood in the castle possessing the minions of Dracula, also it is never explained why you travel back to the castle.In conclusion: this game is mediocre. All of it. The combat is the same as the first entry but you as a player don't need to develop it to conquer the game, there is no need for it. The map, the map is a mess. The bosses don't have any essence to them (in a story way) and have no mechanics whatsoever, just two or three of them. The premise of the story was amazing! It could have been taking through a glorious path and end on an epic note, but instead you get a story that feels dull and no closure at all.Don't play this game if you haven't. Just stay with Lords of Shadow 1 and Mirror of Fate. This is a waste of your time."
