76561198089907009,Not Recommended,239250,9382172,"Posted: 8 March, 2014",all,ConmanWolf,"Did you like the first game in this series? Well, you might find this one annoying then.The first major problem is that unlike the first game, this one is much shorter. You can beat it in about 6-8 hours. That's a decent run time, but then you realize there is nothing else. The game even feels like less is going on, even when a lot of stuff is happening. And not in a good way.The story is this:Gabriel Belmont is Dracula. He wants to die. Because being Dracula is really rough. Now it's the future, and he wakes up. Death shows up and tells Dracula that if they defeat Satan together, than Dracula can have a weapon that will give him eternal rest. Dracula agrees, and it's off to hunt down three of Satan's kids to save the world.Seems like a simple story, right? Well, it kinda isn't. Dracula ends up world hopping from time to time. This means he travels between two totally different world maps. A city, and a castle. The castle is a highly detailed and very pretty wonderland. It's well designed, tons of interesting enemies, and great atmosphere. The castle areas are the best enviornments in the game. Unfortunetly, the castle areas are also home to the worst bits of story. You mostly spend time running around, talking to characters from related to the lore. This also includes Dracula's dead wife and son, who ask you to preform fetch quests for them. At the end, you fight Dracula's inner evil, and the castle section is dead forever. No more use out that.The city on the other hand is the worst. Everything is grey and looks alike. All the good will of the castle and it's varied enviornments is sucked away by the fact that Dracula can't jump over a fence. Running around the city area is difficult too, as the layout is poor and often trying to cram too much into too little space. I got lost a great number of times just trying to go back the way I came because they force you to take different routes all the time. The enemies are mutated humans who somehow manage to be able to block your strongest attacks by using a shotgun as a shield. The other enemies are humans in mech suits, which are easily amongst the most annoying since they fly outside your range and have high damage dealing guns. They even come equiped with shields to block the attacks that do land.But the City part is where all the story happens. All the important, interesting, story details go on in the city. But the boss battles suffer even then. Boss fights in the city are single stage moments with more cutscene than combat, in comparison to the more interesting and BETTER boss fights found at the castle. Clearly there was a conflict during development.The game seems split most of the time actually. It feels like there was a great deal of splits amongst the developers, as some stuff feels a lot less fleshed out. Especially since the ending is flat and awful. Nothing feels resolved, and I guess this was done so that you would still be able to free roam through the city and pick up the collectables you missed.And now, for something that some may be a bit confused by. But the game needed more Quick Time Events. OR at least a better allocation of those QTEs. Let me explain. The bosses are completely void of quick time events. But, there is still a quick time event to open a door. The QTEs for the bosses was deemed LESS important than the QTEs to open the door. It just seems odd to me. And in a way makes the ability to turn off QTEs utterly pointless since there aren't enough to justify the option.The combat is better though. The gameplay has been improved. But oddly enough, the difficulty has raised quite a lot. But not in the good way. Instead of making the enemies more interesting to fight, they no longer stagger, have more health, and tend to swarm. Most have shields that require a three hit combo from your chaos guantlets. The chaos guantlets are really slow, have poor range, drain magic, and the enemies tend to dodge after the second hit, so the third hit rarely hits. And that's if you even manage to get a full combo off since the enemies attack so often you spend most of your time dodging instead of attacking. The game even brings in enemies later in the game who summon more enemies, and have unblockable attacks.The game isn't bad. But is a sad sequel to the first Lords of Shadow."
