76561198018443943,Recommended,239250,29928941,Posted: 14 February,all,Cadis Etrama Di Raziel,"There are times where I both loved and hated Castlevania: Lords of Shadow 2.  I really like the first Lords of Shadow, with the Gothic setting, the fresh character design, the story, and the many diverse/fun situations.  Lords of Shadow 2 is at its best when it puts the player in dynamic combat where you are Dracula, the Prince of Darkness, laying waste to whoever dares to stand against you.  However, the stealth sections felt both tedious and illogical  (why would the strongest vampire on the planet be afraid of some trash mobs, with big guns sure, and pushed to hide?  I mean Satan and Death itself are afraid of him...  I don't get it).Pros:+ Great artistic direction.+ Dynamic combat.+ Great boss battles.+ You play as mothereffing DRACULA, the DRAGON!!+ I enjoyed both the Gothic & Sciebce Fiction settings.+ Great voice acting.Cons:- Stealth sections.- The overall world map is tedious to navigate.- Could have benefited of more combo variety and powers (remember the animation HELLSING, that's a bad♥♥♥♥♥vampire).Verdict: B+"
76561198045234824,Recommended,239250,29657255,Posted: 2 February,all,sascomander,"So as my third Castlevania game ever I found this game to be interesting. Obviously my first 2 are the other Lords of Shadow games on steam. Lords of Shadow 1 and Mirror of Fate.I have to start out saying this game at max settings with the texture pack on is beutiful. Atleast the environments are, the character models are about the same as in the first lords of shadow game. But the Marble floors and walls look amazing same with the castle.The gameplay is 99% the same as the first lords of shadow lots of X and Y if you are using a controller, it has full controller support so I dont see why you wouldnt be. There is 1 change which I found annoying. They switched the function of the right trigger and B button on an Xbox controller from the first game. In the first game right trigger was used to pick stuff up and now its B. This threw me off as it is bascially the only controll change.SPOILERS.I found this game to be more enjoyable than the first but I liked the story in the first one more. This story is confusing.So in the first one you were sent on a mighty quest to kill the three lords of Shadows, Werewolf, Vampire, and Grim Reaper man. This one you are gearing up to fight Satan in a modernish city.There are basically no puzzles in this one which were prevelent in the first one. They have been replaced instead with weird stealth sections. Which absolutly make no sense as you are Dracula who is going to destroy Satan but dies in 2 seconds these large mutant guards with basically rocket launchers in futuristic armor. Very annoying.There is also a sub plot with the castle which was destroyed at the start of the game. Then it sort of becomes its own dimension were stupid BS things happen. Like the blood of the castle is trying to keep him there and basically Mutates anything it touches.Also Zobek is a business man now.I am notgoing thru the entire story but its basically you awake its the future you are in modern city, there are people trying to sommin Satan, you beat them and other bosses , then fight Satan and an old god. With weird BS stuff happening in your Castle dimensional realm.I think the castle became the new Shadow plane maybe? Idk it isnt really explained.8/10 is what I give it."
76561198048427992,Recommended,239250,35506260,Posted: 5 October,all,LazyBone9,"Interesting followup to the first game. Lords of Shadows 2 takes place after the events of Mirror of Fate and in two different timelines. It takes place in modern day where a city has built upon the foundations of Dracula's castle, and in the past, through a strange time-travel sequence that may also be inside your head. But maybe it isn't in your head........or is it?It's confusing.Don't try to understand it.If you're looking for a great sequel that builds upon the first game into an engaging experience you probably won't find it here. It still has plenty of hack n' slash fun, and many great features; do not be fooled however, it is not nearly as polished as its predecessor.While the time travel/in your head sequences may be strange at first it does follow a certain controlled chaos. The game doesn't build as much investment in characters either. In the first game I enjoyed taking Gabriel through his trials to defeat the Lords of Shadows. In this game, while the goal is clear, I never found myself caring all too much.I still recommend playing it through at least once, though not at full price. I picked my copy up during a Steam sale and I think that's the best way to enjoy the game."
